[2]
Date: 10 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Volkskrant [9 Jul 2002] [Trans. provided by Mod.AS] [edited]
The following additional data are derived from the Dutch daily "Volkskrant"
of 9 July
<http://zoek.volkskrant.nl/artikel?text3Dkip%3B%etiket&FDOC0&SORTpresence&PRD10y&ED3D%2A&ADOC>

1. Due to import tariffs, the Dutch plants import deep-frozen chicken from
cheap sources outside the EU. The additives are intended to improve their
tenderness, and sometimes the taste as well. (methods - eg "Tumbling" -
covered in the previous ProMED-mail posting [see references below]).

2. In order to secure the water contents of the chicken meat, some plants
have added animal products such as collagen, which is not necessarily of
chicken origin but may be derived from pigs and cattle.

3. DNA of the said species was detected by the Irish in chicken breast
filets from five Dutch suppliers. In one case, the protein was of milk
origin, in the other ones no clear clarification could be obtained.

4. On top of not-mentioning the additives on the labels, some of the
chicken were signed "Halal" approved for Muslims, in spite of the
pig-protein which is taboo for them.

5. The tests in Great Britain have indicated, mainly, bovine material in
the filets. The matter has two aspects - first, such product is taboo for
Hindus; secondly , there is the BSE issue. However, the Dutch Commodities
Inspection Service regards this fear as unrealistic since risk material -
such as bovine brains - has been kept out of the food chain already for
five years.
